story.text: Giving words to the constraints that make software engineering hard can help us improve. 1. We cannot escape the adaptive universe. 2. We cannot reduce the complexity in the long run. 3. We cannot step outside our local perspective. 4. We cannot do it alone. All we can do is learn to navigate these constraints better. Why This Stuff is Hard by Dr. Lorin Hochstein @ SREcon 23 Americas [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm_qS5raszw youtube] [https://www.usenix.org/conference/srecon23americas/presentation/hochstein usenix]

YOUTUBE Tm_qS5raszw
Why This Stuff is Hard by Dr. Lorin Hochstein @ SREcon 23 Americas [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm_qS5raszw youtube]
# Adaptive Universe
Two rules: 1) resources are finite and 2) change never stops.
Never enough time. Never enough people.
The Law of Stretched Systems. Our systems always run at the limits of our capacity. As soon as we add capacity to a system, the extra capacity will be quickly applied to doing more work.
Opposing forces push us into double binds: get those features out but don't break anything; planing our next cycle comes at the expense of time to reflect on the last cycle;
Unceasing change [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm_qS5raszw&t=444s @7m24s]

Compare code freezes to certificate expiration. We attempt to reduce the change during higher stakes time windows for our business. But some change cannot be controlled: e.g. time ticking past midnight UTC on the date of expiration for TLS certificates. Cert expiration happens with a failure to take action at the right time. Just one example. The world changes around you no matter where you draw your system boundary.
Complexity is Inevitable [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm_qS5raszw&t=869s @14m29s]
We all have an intuition that if there's a lot of boxes and a lot of arrows going between the boxes, that's complex.

Every time like we make changes to the system to prevent failure modes from happening, often after an incident, we are making our systems more complex. The nature of our work to increase the robustness of our systems is always increasing complexity in the long run. We actually have to increase complexity to make our systems better.
Ashby's Law of Requisite Variety [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm_qS5raszw&t=917s @15m17s]

I find that name not very illuminating, so I'll explain it with a toy problem called the inverted pendulum problem. Imagine a cart on rails with an inverted pendulum mounted to the cart. You could develop a control system to measure the angle of the pendulum from vertical and adjust the position of the cart to keep the pendulum balanced above the cart. Now imagine that you add another degree of freedom for the pendulum so the problem becomes like balancing a broom in your hand. The control system from the one-dimensional degree of movement would completely fail with that additional range of motion. We would have to increase the complexity of the control system to manage the more complex range of motion.

[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm_qS5raszw&t=1073s @17m53s] We build in better control, when our original system couldn't handle a certain failure mode. We have to add stuff so that it can, even if it's adding an alert. We're creating a more complex model. Inherently our systems are going to get more complex. When you make them more complex they get weird. You get really weird failure modes from the things that you have built to keep things handling these failure modes.
# Local Point of View

[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm_qS5raszw&t=1167s @19m27s] This is a fundamental aspect of reality. We can all only see one part of the system. There's this entire system that we have to deal with, and we only ever get to see a little bit of it.

This engineer sees a local part of the system, represented here by a cone of vision from the engineer's eyes to a circle around three boxes connected by arrows. Outside the circle are another dozen boxes connected by arrows that are outside the engineer's cone of vision.

Giving words to the constraints that make software engineering hard can help us improve: adaptive universe, unending complexity, single point-of-view, coordination, and what to do about it.
